b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe34019.htm)  [Next](sbe34021.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1417930306/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n_The Vedanta Sutras, commentary by Sankaracharya (SBE34)_ , tr. by George\nThibaut [1890] at sacred-texts.com\n\n* * *\n\n14\\. And because he is declared to be the cause of it, (i.e. of bliss;\ntherefore maya is to be taken as denoting abundance.)\n\nMaya must be understood to denote abundance, for that reason also that\nScripture declares Brahman to be the cause of bliss, 'For he alone causes\nbliss' (Taitt. Up. II, 7). For he who causes bliss must himself abound in\nbliss; just as we infer in ordinary life, that a man who enriches others must\nhimself possess abundant wealth. As, therefore, maya may be taken to mean\n'abundant,' the Self consisting of bliss is the highest Self.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: I, 1, 15](sbe34021.htm)\n\n"